00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:48.970
metric, et cetera.

00:49:48.970 --> 00:49:51.110
And if you have not seen
a Schwarzschild metric,

00:49:51.110 --> 00:49:51.785
it's also OK.

00:49:54.630 --> 00:50:01.000
I think you should be able to
follow what I'm going to say.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:03.616
So for simplicity, right
now let me consider

00:50:03.616 --> 00:50:04.740
zero cosmological constant.

00:50:09.700 --> 00:50:13.750
OK, zero cosmological constant.

00:50:17.610 --> 00:50:20.150
OK, zero cosmological
constant corresponding to-- we

00:50:20.150 --> 00:50:25.600
consider symptotically
Minkowski space time.

00:50:25.600 --> 00:50:30.920
And so in the space time of zero
cosmological constant entered

00:50:30.920 --> 00:50:45.120
in the space time metric
due to an object of mass m.

00:50:49.736 --> 00:51:04.545
It can be written as-- so this
is the famous Schwarzschild

00:51:04.545 --> 00:51:05.045
metric.

00:51:33.350 --> 00:51:38.980
And so of course
here we are assuming

00:51:38.980 --> 00:51:50.000
this is a spherical symmetric,
and a neutral, et cetera.

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:52.630
So this object does
not carry any charge.

00:51:55.480 --> 00:52:04.610
And this m and this f--
it's given by 1 minus 2m,

00:52:04.610 --> 00:52:10.810
mass divided by r, or it's
equal to rs divided by r.

00:52:10.810 --> 00:52:13.910
OK, so this rs is the
Schwarzschild radius.

00:52:14.620 --> 00:52:17.150
So now c is always equal to 1.

00:52:24.280 --> 00:52:27.980
So if this object-- so
we consider this object

00:52:27.980 --> 00:52:29.320
is very close metric center.

00:52:29.320 --> 00:52:35.280
If this object have finite
sides, then of course

00:52:35.280 --> 00:52:37.935
this metric only is varied
outside this object.

00:52:40.830 --> 00:52:45.140
But if the sides
of this object is

00:52:45.140 --> 00:52:49.350
smaller than the
Schwarzschild radius,

00:52:49.350 --> 00:52:50.480
then this is a black hole.

00:52:50.480 --> 00:53:04.510
OK, and the black hold is
distinguished by event horizon

00:53:04.510 --> 00:53:07.980
and r equal to rs.

00:53:07.980 --> 00:53:10.220
OK, and the r equal to rs.

00:53:10.220 --> 00:53:15.610
So at r equal to rs, you
see that this f becomes 0.

00:53:15.610 --> 00:53:18.220
OK, so f equals become 0.

00:53:18.220 --> 00:53:26.800
So essentially at here gtt-- so
the metric for the tt component

00:53:26.800 --> 00:53:35.720
is becomes 0, and the grr, the
metric before the r component

00:53:35.720 --> 00:53:36.445
become infinite.

00:53:41.760 --> 00:53:49.300
And another thing is that when
r becomes smaller than rs,

00:53:49.300 --> 00:53:50.845
the f switch sign.

00:53:57.540 --> 00:54:04.270
So f become active, and then
in this case then the r become

00:54:04.270 --> 00:54:07.850
time coordinates and the t
becomes spatial coordinates,

00:54:07.850 --> 00:54:12.206
when you go inside
to the r equal to rs.

00:54:12.206 --> 00:54:14.450
OK, this is just a
feature of this metric.

00:54:17.490 --> 00:54:24.720
So now let me say some simple
fact about this metric.

00:54:34.420 --> 00:54:38.660
So most of them I
expect you know--

00:54:38.660 --> 00:54:40.120
I expect you know of them.

00:54:45.710 --> 00:54:52.290
But just to remind you
some of those facts

00:54:52.290 --> 00:54:54.670
will be important later.

00:54:54.670 --> 00:54:59.800
OK, so these are
mostly reminders.

00:55:03.490 --> 00:55:10.992
So first, this metric-- if you
look at this metric itself,

00:55:10.992 --> 00:55:12.200
it's time reversal invariant.

00:55:20.860 --> 00:55:26.350
OK, because if you
take t go to minus t,

00:55:26.350 --> 00:55:31.070
of course the invariant
on the t goes to minus t.

00:55:31.070 --> 00:55:35.350
OK, so this-- actually,
because of this,

00:55:35.350 --> 00:55:39.320
this cannot describe
a real black hole.

00:55:39.320 --> 00:55:45.010
So the real life black hole
arise from the gravitational

00:55:45.010 --> 00:55:48.650
collapse, and the gravitational
collapse cannot be a time

00:55:48.650 --> 00:55:50.270
symmetric process, OK?

00:55:50.270 --> 00:55:53.200
So this cannot describe-- so
this does not describe a real

00:55:53.200 --> 00:55:57.830
black hole, but it's a good
approximation to the real life

00:55:57.830 --> 00:56:01.019
black hole after this
object have stabilized.

00:56:01.019 --> 00:56:03.060
So after the gravitational
collapse has finished.

00:56:05.620 --> 00:56:10.710
So this is a mathematical--
in some sense,

00:56:10.710 --> 00:56:18.859
it is a mathematical
idealization

00:56:18.859 --> 00:56:24.230
of real life black hole.

00:56:27.510 --> 00:56:30.712
OK, so this is first remark.

00:56:35.980 --> 00:56:42.770
So the second remark is that
despite this grr goes infinity,

00:56:42.770 --> 00:56:44.290
this metric component
goes infinity.

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:54.650
So the space time is
non-singular at the horizon.

00:57:02.130 --> 00:57:07.110
OK, so you can check
it by computing,

00:57:07.110 --> 00:57:11.240
say, curvature invariants
of this metric.

00:57:11.240 --> 00:57:14.304
You find the number of the--
all the curvature invariant

00:57:14.304 --> 00:57:15.220
that are well-defined.

00:57:18.040 --> 00:57:22.570
So this horizon is
just the coordinate--

00:57:22.570 --> 00:57:24.600
you can show that
this horizon is just

00:57:24.600 --> 00:57:25.700
a coordinate singularity.

00:57:32.620 --> 00:57:36.360
Which we will see--
actually, we will see it

00:57:36.360 --> 00:57:42.310
in maybe next lecture, or maybe
at the end of today's lecture,

00:57:42.310 --> 00:57:45.430
that just this
coordinate, r and the t,

00:57:45.430 --> 00:57:48.717
coordinate become singular.

00:57:48.717 --> 00:57:50.300
The coordinate itself
become singular.

00:58:08.820 --> 00:58:12.660
So this t, we normally
call it Schwarzschild time.

00:58:12.660 --> 00:58:14.640
So let me just introduce a name.

00:58:14.640 --> 00:58:17.325
So this t, we call it
the Schwarzschild time.

00:58:30.620 --> 00:58:33.050
So Schwarzschild
found this solution

00:58:33.050 --> 00:58:40.860
while fighting first World
War, really in the battlefield.

00:58:40.860 --> 00:58:44.760
And a couple months after
he finished this metric,

00:58:44.760 --> 00:58:46.150
he died from some disease.

00:58:53.490 --> 00:58:54.850
Right, this is that.

00:58:58.740 --> 00:59:05.000
So another thing, you
can easily check yourself

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:12.706
with r equal to rs-- the
horizon is a null surface-- is

00:59:12.706 --> 00:59:13.580
a null hyper surface.

00:59:22.090 --> 00:59:24.160
It's a null hyper surface.

00:59:24.160 --> 00:59:32.670
The null hyper surface just
say this surface contains

00:59:32.670 --> 00:59:34.690
geodesics which are null.

00:59:39.600 --> 00:59:44.690
And this is a-- the third remark
is an extremely important one,

00:59:44.690 --> 00:59:50.680
which we will use many
times in the future.

00:59:50.680 --> 01:00:03.750
We said the horizon is a surface
of infinite red shift compared

01:00:03.750 --> 01:00:13.290
to the-- infinite red shift
from the perspective of observed

01:00:13.290 --> 01:00:15.930
infinity, OK?

01:00:15.930 --> 01:00:19.500
So let me save time, now, to
add to this qualifying remark

01:00:19.500 --> 01:00:23.440
from the perspective
of observed infinity.

01:00:23.440 --> 01:00:28.100
So now let me just illustrate
this point a little bit more

01:00:28.100 --> 01:00:30.000
explicitly.

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:39.550
So let's consider observer--
consider an observer-- so

01:00:39.550 --> 01:00:46.550
let me call oh-- at some
hyper surface r, which

01:00:46.550 --> 01:00:51.430
is close to the horizon.

01:00:51.430 --> 01:00:57.060
Yeah, say as someplace which
is close to the horizon.

01:01:01.920 --> 01:01:05.030
Slightly outside the horizon.

01:01:05.030 --> 01:01:08.620
And let us consider
another observer,

01:01:08.620 --> 01:01:16.890
which I call o infinity,
which at i go to infinity.

01:01:16.890 --> 01:01:21.630
OK, very far away
from the black hole.

01:01:21.630 --> 01:01:26.300
So let's first look
at this observer.

01:01:26.300 --> 01:01:34.490
So the i equals infinity,
then your metric-- so at i

01:01:34.490 --> 01:01:37.120
equals infinity, this
f just becomes one,

01:01:37.120 --> 01:01:41.140
because when your r goes to
infinity, this r just become 1.

01:01:41.140 --> 01:01:44.469
And then this become the
standard Minkowski space

01:01:44.469 --> 01:01:46.260
time, written in the
spherical coordinates.

01:01:49.250 --> 01:01:59.130
So we just have the standard
Minkowski time written

01:01:59.130 --> 01:02:01.340
in spherical coordinates.

01:02:01.340 --> 01:02:03.133
And then from here
you can immediately

01:02:03.133 --> 01:02:08.050
see-- so this t is what we
call Schwarzschild time.

01:02:08.050 --> 01:02:16.100
t is the proper time for
this observed infinity.

01:02:16.100 --> 01:02:18.580
Say, for o infinity.

01:02:18.580 --> 01:02:30.210
OK, so now let's look at
someplace i equal to rh.

01:02:30.210 --> 01:02:37.330
So at i equal to
rh, then the metric

01:02:37.330 --> 01:02:44.690
is given by minus f rh
dt squared with the rest.

01:02:44.690 --> 01:02:53.090
OK, and to define the proper
time for the observer at-- we

01:02:53.090 --> 01:02:55.875
can just directly write
it as minus d tau squared.

01:02:55.875 --> 01:02:59.020
So that's the proper
time observed by observer

01:02:59.020 --> 01:03:02.360
at this hyper surface, OK?

01:03:02.360 --> 01:03:06.370
So then we concludes--
so let me call it tau h.

01:03:06.370 --> 01:03:12.818
So we conclude that
the problem time for oh

01:03:12.818 --> 01:03:18.610
is given by f 1/2 rh times dt.

01:03:18.610 --> 01:03:22.050
OK, so it relates to the
proper time at infinity

01:03:22.050 --> 01:03:22.884
by this factor.

01:03:28.460 --> 01:03:31.670
So if I write it more
explicitly-- so this

01:03:31.670 --> 01:03:37.670
is 1 minus rh, divided
by rs 1/2 times dt.

01:03:46.090 --> 01:04:12.860
So we see that as rh--
suppose this observer--

01:04:12.860 --> 01:04:19.520
the location of this observer
approach the horizon, say,

01:04:19.520 --> 01:04:26.850
if rh approach to rs, then
this d tau h divided by dt

01:04:26.850 --> 01:04:27.760
will go to 0.

01:04:35.730 --> 01:04:44.560
So that means
compared to the time

01:04:44.560 --> 01:05:02.740
at infinity the time at r equal
to rs becomes infinite now.

01:05:02.740 --> 01:05:06.200
So-- or approximate, let me
say, becomes infinite now.

01:05:18.860 --> 01:05:24.730
So that means any
finite interval--

01:05:24.730 --> 01:05:30.550
any finite proper time
interval for observer at oh--

01:05:30.550 --> 01:05:35.560
for this oh-- when you
view [INAUDIBLE] infinity

01:05:35.560 --> 01:05:37.640
become infinitely null, OK?

01:05:37.640 --> 01:05:39.890
Become very long time scale.

01:05:39.890 --> 01:05:41.860
OK, become very long time scale.

01:05:41.860 --> 01:05:49.710
So you can also
invert this relation.

01:05:49.710 --> 01:05:54.170
OK, you can also invert
the recent relation.

01:05:54.170 --> 01:06:02.980
Say, suppose some
event of energy

01:06:02.980 --> 01:06:15.282
with energy eh--
with proper energy

01:06:15.282 --> 01:06:23.790
eh-- say, for this observer
at oh, for this observer oh.

01:06:23.790 --> 01:06:31.750
Then because of the time
relation between them,

01:06:31.750 --> 01:06:34.800
because of the time
relation between them,

01:06:34.800 --> 01:06:45.170
then from the perspective
of this observer at infinity

01:06:45.170 --> 01:06:50.470
the energy is given just but
you invert the [INAUDIBLE]

01:06:50.470 --> 01:06:54.600
between the time, because of
the energy and time conjugate.

01:06:54.600 --> 01:07:00.040
So the e infinity becomes
eh times this f 1/2 rh.

01:07:05.100 --> 01:07:10.100
So for this just again says,
in a slightly different way,

01:07:10.100 --> 01:07:19.780
that for any finite eh local
proper energy-- so this

01:07:19.780 --> 01:07:26.000
is a local proper energy
for the observer at oh--

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:30.160
this e infinity--
the same event viewed

01:07:30.160 --> 01:07:35.130
form the perspective of the
observer at infinity goes to 0.

01:07:35.130 --> 01:07:39.500
S rh goes to rs.

01:07:39.500 --> 01:07:52.960
So that e is infinity
red shifted--

01:07:52.960 --> 01:07:54.430
become infinite red shift.

01:07:54.430 --> 01:08:00.930
So any process with
local proper energy

01:08:00.930 --> 01:08:02.940
viewed from infinity
corresponding

01:08:02.940 --> 01:08:06.520
to very, very low
energy process.

01:08:06.520 --> 01:08:09.130
So this actually will play
a very important role.

01:08:09.130 --> 01:08:11.630
This feature will play
a very important role

01:08:11.630 --> 01:08:14.303
when later we talk about
holographic duality

01:08:14.303 --> 01:08:18.382
and it's implication, say, for
