01:09:51.189 --> 01:10:03.780
So number four is that it takes
a free fall-- free fall means

01:10:03.780 --> 01:10:12.410
we just follow geodesics--
free fall of a traveler

01:10:12.410 --> 01:10:23.160
a finite proper time
to reach the horizon--

01:10:23.160 --> 01:10:39.614
say, from the infinity-- but
infinite Schwarzschild time.

01:10:48.560 --> 01:10:50.440
So also you can easily
check that it actually

01:10:50.440 --> 01:10:53.770
takes infinite Schwarzschild
time for object

01:10:53.770 --> 01:10:55.960
to fall through the horizon.

01:10:55.960 --> 01:10:58.830
But from the free
fall observer itself,

01:10:58.830 --> 01:11:02.440
it's actually just
finite proper time.

01:11:02.440 --> 01:11:06.760
And so from the perspective
of the observer at infinity,

01:11:06.760 --> 01:11:11.330
it looks like this object
never fall into the black hole.

01:11:11.330 --> 01:11:14.470
It's just frozen at the horizon.

01:11:14.470 --> 01:11:27.740
So another remark is that
once inside the horizon-- that

01:11:27.740 --> 01:11:33.250
means when r becomes
smaller than rs--

01:11:33.250 --> 01:12:03.230
the traveler can not
send signals to outside,

01:12:03.230 --> 01:12:05.528
nor can he escape.

01:12:09.350 --> 01:12:11.970
So that's why this is
called even horizon.

01:12:11.970 --> 01:12:16.290
So we will see this
slightly later.

01:12:16.290 --> 01:12:18.155
In next lecture we will
see this explicitly.

01:12:21.890 --> 01:12:28.530
So finally, there are two
important geometric quantities

01:12:28.530 --> 01:12:31.197
associated with the horizon.

01:12:31.197 --> 01:12:50.159
Two important geometric-- OK?

01:12:52.680 --> 01:13:02.130
So the first one is the
area of the spatial section.

01:13:02.130 --> 01:13:08.410
So suppose-- so let's consider
we are at i equal to rs,

01:13:08.410 --> 01:13:12.120
and then here you just
said r equal to rs,

01:13:12.120 --> 01:13:15.357
and then this is a
two-dimensional sphere, OK?

01:13:15.357 --> 01:13:17.190
So this two-dimensional
sphere corresponding

01:13:17.190 --> 01:13:19.490
to a spatial section
of the horizon.

01:13:22.890 --> 01:13:33.499
So first, A is the area
of a spatial section.

01:13:40.360 --> 01:13:46.600
So you can just say let's
look at the area of this part

01:13:46.600 --> 01:13:50.210
with the r equal to
the horizon radius.

01:13:50.210 --> 01:13:55.820
So this just give you a
equal to ah ah, equal to 4

01:13:55.820 --> 01:13:59.030
pi rs squared.

01:13:59.030 --> 01:14:12.370
And this rs is 2GN, so this
become 16 pi GN squared.

01:14:12.370 --> 01:14:16.520
OK, so this is one of the key
quantities of a black hole

